ym xml:lang="en">It is probably a substratum European word; cf. <mentioned xml:lang="fr"><lang/> <w>pic</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="it"><lang/> <w>picco</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="es"><lang/> <w>pico</w> <gloss><q>peak</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="es"><w/> <gloss><q>edge</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="es"><w/> <gloss><q>beak</q></gloss></mentioned>,  etc. Probably, the following words also refer here: <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/> <w>pekʼe</w> <gloss><q>tip</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/> <w>bik</w> <gloss><q>stump</q></gloss></mentioned>. It is quite possible that all of these words appeared because of sound symbolysm, like the group of words considered in the word <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tymbyl"/>.</etym></entry></body></text></TEI>